  "text": "The use of nanoparticles in medicine is increasingly gaining attention, mainly in cancer-related therapies, but also extending to HIV, asthma, and other infections [CITATION_1] . While only a few nanoparticle-based drugs have made the translation to the clinic [2] , they show great promise in, for example, reducing toxicity [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . They provide a versatile platform for theranostic approaches, allowing for easy surface modification and/or encapsulation of drugs and contrast agents. There are a number of well-established factors which have to be taken into account when designing nanocarrier studies resulting in the",
